title: Labor’s net zero approach is ‘killing small business’
description: Shadow Resources Minister Susan McDonald says Labor’s net zero approach is “killing small business”.  Ms McDonald told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio that net zero is “not going well” for Australia.  “And we are all completely united in finding a better way to achieve an energy policy.”

title: ‘Madness’: Albanese government pushes more ‘very left wing’ policies
description: Shadow Resources Minister Susan McDonald calls out the “madness” within the Albanese Labor government.  Ms McDonald told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio that there are older Labor members “shaking their heads” in shame at the modern party.  “And frustration at what’s happening under this very left-wing Labor government.”

title: Princess Anne arrives in Australia for ‘military engagements’
description: Royal Commentator Victoria Arbiter discusses the arrival of Princess Anne in Australia as she begins her four-day trip to celebrate the Centenary of the Royal Australian Corps of Signals.  “They were formed in 1925, Princess Anne became their Colonel-in-Chief in 1977,” Ms Arbiter told Sky News Australia.  “Quite an extraordinary commitment  …. associated with the court for 48 years.  “The next four days are going to see a series of military engagements.”

title: ‘Incredibly committed’: Princess Anne touches down in Australia
description: Royal Commentator Victoria Arbiter says Princess Anne is “incredibly committed” and “gets on with the job at hand,” as she arrives in Australia to commemorate the Centenary of the Royal Australian Corps of Signals.  “She's not one for a lot of fuss, she just likes to hit the ground running,” Ms Arbiter told Sky News Australia.  “For her, it's going to be all about putting the focus on the people that she's meeting … veterans, current serving personnel, and indeed the families associated with those serving personnel.”

title: ‘She might acknowledge it’: Princess Anne lands in Australia in the midst of Andrew’s exile
description: Royal Commentator Victoria Arbiter predicts Princess Anne will get “to the point and move quickly on” if questioned on Andrew’s exile, following a “similar cause” to Prince William. ​ “She might acknowledge it with a look, there may be a raised eyebrow,” Ms Arbiter told Sky News Australia. ​ “Andrew has been something of a dark cloud hanging over the Royal Family for a number of years.”

title: ‘Pressure’ is on Trump to resolve shutdown in time for ‘Thanksgiving’
description: United States Studies Centre Associate Harry Melkonian states the “pressure” is on US President Donald Trump to resolve the government shutdown in time for ‘Thanksgiving’ as flight cancellations hit major airports.    Mr Melkonian told Sky News Australia, Thanksgiving is the “biggest air traffic period in the United States”.  “A substantial cutback in domestic travel … would be catastrophic and would put enormous pressure on the White House and on Congress.  “The public is not going to be very forgiving … when you’ve got millions of people who want to fly home for the holiday.”

title: Democrats have ‘upper hand’ as more Americans lose ‘tolerance’ with US government shutdown
description: United States Studies Centre Associate Harry Melkonian believes the US government shutdown will be resolved “in the next week”.  “The majority of people are going to be affected by this  … they certainly have lost tolerance,” Mr Melkonian told Sky News Australia.  “Normally, it's the president who takes the blame …   so for the moment, you might say the Democrats have the upper hand.”

title: ‘It's a peculiarity’: US government shutdowns aren't ‘common at all’
description: United States Studies Centre Associate Harry Melkonian says US government shutdowns are not ‘common at all’ with the political process “normally” reaching “accommodation”.  Mr Melkonian told Sky News Australia, “Republicans had the majority,” but they couldn't bring the “matter to a vote in the Senate”.  “It takes a super majority to bring the matter to a vote, and the Republicans don't have a super majority.

title: Sussan Ley can ‘survive’ the net zero battle
description: Former NSW Police minister David Elliott says Opposition Leader Sussan Ley can “survive” the net-zero split.  “The team has to be united, they need to get their narrative together … dump net-zero,” Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “We are seeing a lot of indecision.”

title: Sussan Ley may have to ‘call it a day’ as net-zero policy splits the Liberals
description: NSW Independent MP Tania Mihailuk states the concerns being raised by members in the Liberal Party show “people are worried” about their “own personal seats”.  “I think eventually Sussan Ley will have to call it a day,” Ms Mihailuk told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “We want a healthy Opposition.”

title: ‘Rally the troops’: Surge in support for One Nation
description: Former NSW Police minister David Elliott discusses a surge in support for Pauline Hanson’s One Nation as their membership base doubles.  “This is proof positive that we are actually going to need some right-wing warriors to go to these One Nation devotees,” Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “We need them in to rally the troops.  “Handpick some good conservatives that will go back out into the One Nation field and say come back to the Liberal Party.”

title: One Nation will ‘never’ have the ‘capacity’ to form a government: NSW Independent MP
description: NSW Independent MP Tania Mihailuk calls Pauline Hanson a “strong leader,” but One Nation will “never” have the “capacity” to form a government.  “The biggest problem One Nation has is that they don't have the structure or the ability to be an alternative government,” Ms Mihailuk told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “The Liberal Party does have the capacity.” ​

title: The public sector doesn't need any more ‘’cardigan-wearing biscuit munchers’ in offices
description: Former NSW Police minister David Elliott highlights Australians need a “department” to identify where the growth in public sector jobs is going and where they are “needed”.    “We need cops, we need soldiers, so they are public sector jobs that we need to have employed on the taxpayers' dime,” Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “We don't need cardigan-wearing biscuit munchers that are sitting in offices.”

title: ‘Good on her’: Sydney Sweeney doesn't apologise for American Eagle ad
description: Former Liberal senator Hollie Hughes commends Actress Sydney Sweeney for refusing to apologise for the American Eagle ad, which faced backlash from the left.  “I wasn't a big fan of her as an actress …  but the way that she’s handled this, well, I’m a convert,” Ms Hughes told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “Good on her.”

title: ‘Team behind’ Ley fuelling the fire to Coalition’s chaos
description: Former Liberal senator Hollie Hughes states it’s the “team behind” Opposition Leader Sussan Ley fuelling the Coalition chaos on net-zero.  “There are some people with more ambition than conviction,” Ms Hughes told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “They are not working as a team, while we are looking at one of the worst governments in history.  “And yet there is a group within the Liberal Party unable to get on board.”
